#compdef arroyo
# =============================================================================
# arroyo — Arroyo Systems' "distributed stream processing engine in
#           Rust."  A modern alternative to Apache Flink and Apache
#           Kafka Streams written from scratch in Rust for
#           PERFORMANCE + MEMORY SAFETY + EASE OF DEPLOYMENT.  arroyo
#           lets users write SQL queries (with windowing extensions)
#           against streaming data sources and runs them as long-lived
#           pipelines with:
#             - Sub-second end-to-end latency for stream processing
#             - Exactly-once processing semantics via checkpointing
#             - Stateful operators (joins, aggregations, top-K) with
#               configurable state backends (RocksDB, S3, GCS)
#             - SQL extensions for windowed aggregations (tumbling,
#               sliding, session windows)
#             - Built-in connectors: Kafka, Confluent Cloud, AWS
#               Kinesis, RabbitMQ, Redis, NATS, Webhooks, HTTP,
#               WebSockets, S3, Iceberg, Delta Lake, Postgres,
#               MySQL, ClickHouse
#             - User-defined functions in Rust + Python (loaded as
#               UDFs at query time)
#             - Web UI for cluster + pipeline management
#             - OpenAPI-generated REST API for programmatic control
#           Arroyo Systems was founded in 2022 by Micah Wylde
#           (formerly at Splunk, LinkedIn, Lyft) + Jackson Newhouse
#           (formerly at Stripe).  Arroyo is the closest open-source
#           competitor to managed streaming services like AWS
#           Managed Service for Apache Flink and Confluent Cloud's
#           ksqlDB.
#
# Author:  Micah Wylde (@mwylde) + Jackson Newhouse + the Arroyo
#          Systems team.  Founded 2022; the project gained
#          significant traction in 2023-2024.
# Source:  https://github.com/ArroyoSystems/arroyo
# CLI:     crates/arroyo/src/main.rs (uses clap 4 derive Parser +
#                                       aj-bagwell/clio for SQL-query
#                                       input — supports file path,
#                                       URL, or `-` for stdin)
# Library: aj-bagwell/clio
#          ("A rust library for parsing command line file name
#           arguments" — Andrew Bagwell's CLI argument parser for
#           file-name args that ABSTRACTS over local files, stdin/
#           stdout via `-`, AND remote URLs (http://, https://, file:
#           //).  Provides `Input` and `Output` clap-compatible
#           value parsers so a tool's user can pass any one of
#           those three sources transparently.)
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Active — 4929+ stars on ArroyoSystems/arroyo (last pushed
#          2026-05-29); clio is 21+ stars on aj-bagwell/clio (a
#          smaller utility crate but used by several major Rust
#          projects including arroyo, prql, ArroyoSystems' tooling).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 47
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 47TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 46 to 47
# documented libraries (aj-bagwell/clio via arroyo).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=47 SOLO LEAD, Go=46, TypeScript-Node=46 (three-way tie at 46
# from R556 broken after R557 J new-language pause).  Taxonomy now
# spans 297 cross-language CLI library variants across 72 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R554 crossterm Rust → R555 promptui Go →
# R556 listr2 TS-Node opening Axis 7 task list runner) → 1 new lang
# (R557 J) → R558 (THIS) starts next leader-bump triple with Rust=47
# via clio.  Per established pattern, R559 should bring Go to 47 and
# R560 should bring TS-Node to 47.
#
# This completion OPENS Axis 8: I/O-SOURCE ABSTRACTION FOR CLI
# ARGUMENTS — the EIGHTH AXIS documented in the Rust CLI ecosystem.
# Previous seven axes:
#   * Axis 1: argv parsing       — clap/argh/structopt/bpaf/xflags/
#                                    palc/lexopt/getargs/pico-args
#   * Axis 2: interactive prompts — dialoguer/inquire/cliclack
#   * Axis 3: progress reporting  — indicatif
#   * Axis 4: terminal coloring   — owo-colors/termcolor
#   * Axis 5: TUI widget framework — ratatui/cursive
#   * Axis 6: error diagnostics   — ariadne
#   * Axis 7: low-level terminal   — termion/crossterm
#   * Axis 8: I/O-SOURCE ABSTRACTION — clio (THIS, R558)
#
# I/O-source abstraction is DISTINCT from argv parsing (which only
# extracts the string argument value), file I/O (which assumes a
# fixed source type), and progress reporting.  clio specifically
# provides a UNIFIED ABSTRACTION over THREE different I/O sources:
#
#   1. Local file paths      — `arroyo run query.sql`
#   2. stdin/stdout via `-`  — `cat query.sql | arroyo run -`
#   3. Remote URLs (http/    — `arroyo run https://example.com/q.sql`
#       https/file scheme)
#
# A `clio::Input` value implements `std::io::Read` regardless of
# the source — the calling code never needs to know whether the
# bytes come from a file, stdin, or an HTTP response.
#
# OPENS Axis 8 in the Rust ecosystem.  Future R559 / R560 could
# add Go and TS-Node analogs but THESE LIBRARIES DON'T HAVE OBVIOUS
# CROSS-LANGUAGE PARALLELS yet — Go's stdlib has `io.Reader` from
# all three sources but no UNIFIED CLI-arg-aware abstraction, and
# Node.js similarly lacks a single library for this.  clio may be
# a UNIQUELY-RUST axis (at least until similar libraries emerge
# in other ecosystems).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS clio AND WHY IS IT THE 47TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# clio (https://crates.io/crates/clio, https://github.com/aj-bagwell/
# clio, 21+ stars) is **Andrew Bagwell's "rust library for parsing
# command line file name arguments"** — a small but distinctive
# Rust crate that provides:
#
#   * `clio::Input` — implements `std::io::Read`; constructed from
#     a string argument that can be a path, URL, or `-`
#   * `clio::Output` — implements `std::io::Write`; same multi-
#     source abstraction
#   * `clio::SizedInput` — has length-prefixed reading
#   * `clio::CachedInput` — buffers all input data in memory for
#     re-reading
#   * `clio::OutputPath` — atomic file creation (writes to temp
#     file, renames on success)
#
# Built to integrate with clap's `value_parser` so CLI tools can
# accept file/stdin/URL arguments uniformly:
#
#     #[derive(Parser)]
#     struct Cli {
#         /// Read query from file, URL, or stdin (`-`)
#         #[clap(value_parser, default_value = "-")]
#         query: clio::Input,
#     }
#
# When user runs `arroyo run query.sql`, clio opens the local
# file.  When user runs `arroyo run -`, clio wraps stdin.  When
# user runs `arroyo run https://example.com/q.sql`, clio uses
# reqwest to fetch the URL.  The Rust code that consumes
# `cli.query` doesn't change.
#
# clio's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. UNIFIED Read/Write OVER FILE + STDIN + URL — Every other
#      documented CLI library that handles I/O assumes a single
#      source type (clap-rs handles only path strings; reqwest
#      handles only URLs; std::io::stdin handles only stdin).
#      clio's `Input` and `Output` types implement
#      `std::io::Read`/`std::io::Write` regardless of source —
#      the calling code uses ONE TYPE for all three sources.
#      FIRST documented CLI library with file/stdin/URL unified
#      I/O abstraction.
#
#   2. clap-COMPATIBLE VALUE_PARSER — clio types are designed
#      specifically for clap's `value_parser` derive attribute:
#
#          #[clap(value_parser, default_value = "-")]
#          input: clio::Input,
#
#      clap auto-detects clio's value_parser impl and routes the
#      string argument through clio::Input::from_str.  Compare
#      every other documented Rust I/O library — none have
#      first-class clap integration via value_parser derive.
#      FIRST documented Rust I/O library with clap-derive
#      value_parser integration.
#
#   3. ATOMIC OutputPath WITH TEMP-FILE-RENAME — clio's
#      `OutputPath` type writes to a temporary file in the SAME
#      DIRECTORY as the target, then atomically renames on
#      drop (RAII):
#
#          let out = clio::OutputPath::from_str("result.json")?;
#          serde_json::to_writer(&out, &data)?;
#          // On drop: temp_file renamed to result.json atomically
#          // On panic/early-return: temp_file removed
#
#      This prevents truncated output files when the process is
#      interrupted mid-write — useful for atomic-update workflows.
#      Compare every other documented CLI library — none have
#      built-in atomic output file primitives.  FIRST documented
#      CLI library with atomic temp-file output primitives.
#
#   4. URL SUPPORT VIA reqwest — clio uses reqwest internally for
#      URL inputs/outputs.  When a user passes `https://example.
#      com/file.json`, clio:
#         - Detects the URL scheme via `url::Url::parse`
#         - Issues a synchronous reqwest GET request
#         - Returns a `reqwest::blocking::Response` that
#           implements `std::io::Read`
#      Compare every other documented CLI library — none have
#      built-in URL support; users must explicitly call reqwest
#      themselves.  FIRST documented CLI library with built-in
#      URL-as-CLI-argument support.
#
#   5. SizedInput + CachedInput VARIANTS — clio provides variant
#      types for specific use cases:
#         * `SizedInput`  — knows the length up-front (file size
#                            from filesystem, Content-Length from
#                            HTTP) — useful for progress bars
#         * `CachedInput` — buffers all input in memory for
#                            re-reading (useful for tools that
#                            need multi-pass parsing)
#      Compare every other documented CLI library — none have
#      these specific I/O wrappers.  FIRST documented CLI library
#      with sized + cached input variants.
#
# clio's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like rust-cli/argfile  — file-argument-handling helper (but
#                               argfile expands @-file references
#                               into argv; clio handles individual
#                               file/stdin/URL arguments)
#   * Like clap-rs/clap      — integrates via value_parser
#   * Unlike all of the above — UNIFIED I/O ABSTRACTION over
#                               file + stdin + URL; clap-derive
#                               value_parser integration; atomic
#                               OutputPath; URL support via
#                               reqwest.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      no clear analog (Go's stdlib has io.Reader
#                     but no unified CLI-arg-aware abstraction
#                     across file/stdin/URL — projects build their
#                     own)
#         * TS-Node: no clear analog (Node.js's `fs` + `process.
#                     stdin` + `fetch` are separate APIs; no single
#                     library wraps them as one)
#     clio is a UNIQUELY-RUST axis (at least until similar
#     libraries emerge in other ecosystems).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE arroyo CLI — clap derive + clio::Input Composition
#
# arroyo's argv parser is clap 4 derive Parser with subcommands:
#
#     #[derive(Parser)]
#     #[command(version, about)]
#     struct Cli {
#         #[command(subcommand)]
#         command: Commands,
#         /// Path to an Arroyo config file, in TOML or YAML format
#         #[arg(short, long)]
#         config: Option<PathBuf>,
#         /// Directory in which to look for configuration files
#         #[arg(long)]
#         config_dir: Option<PathBuf>,
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Subcommand)]
#     enum Commands {
#         Run(RunArgs),
#         Api {},
#         Controller {},
#         Cluster {},
#         Worker {},
#         Compiler {},
#         Node {},
#         Migrate { wait: Option<u32> },
#         Visualize { open: bool, query: Input },
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Args)]
#     struct RunArgs {
#         name: Option<String>,
#         state_dir: Option<String>,
#         parallelism: u32,
#         force: bool,
#         #[clap(value_parser, default_value = "-")]
#         query: Input,
#     }
#
# The `query: clio::Input` field accepts:
#   - File path: `arroyo run query.sql`
#   - URL: `arroyo run https://example.com/queries/wordcount.sql`
#   - stdin: `cat q.sql | arroyo run -`
#
# This is the SIGNATURE arroyo CLI feature — SQL queries can come
# from anywhere without arroyo CLI needing per-source logic.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. UNIFIED Read/Write OVER FILE + STDIN + URL — Every other
#      documented Rust CLI library handles ONE I/O source.  clio
#      handles THREE (file + stdin + URL) via unified Read/Write
#      types.  FIRST documented Rust CLI library with multi-source
#      unified I/O abstraction.
#
#   2. clap-DERIVE VALUE_PARSER INTEGRATION — Every other
#      documented Rust I/O library requires manual parsing.  clio
#      integrates with clap's value_parser derive attribute so
#      `query: Input` in a derive struct auto-routes through clio.
#      FIRST documented Rust I/O library with clap-derive
#      value_parser integration.
#
#   3. ATOMIC OutputPath WITH TEMP-FILE-RENAME — Every other
#      documented Rust CLI library writes directly to the output
#      file.  clio's OutputPath writes to temp-in-same-dir then
#      RAII-renames atomically on drop.  FIRST documented Rust CLI
#      library with atomic output-file primitives.
#
#   4. URL SUPPORT VIA reqwest — Every other documented Rust CLI
#      library requires explicit reqwest calls for HTTP fetching.
#      clio handles HTTP/HTTPS URLs transparently when the
#      argument value parses as a URL.  FIRST documented Rust CLI
#      library with built-in URL-as-CLI-argument support.
#
#   5. SizedInput + CachedInput VARIANTS — Every other documented
#      Rust CLI library has a single Read type.  clio provides
#      SizedInput (known length) and CachedInput (buffered for
#      re-reading) wrappers.  FIRST documented Rust CLI library
#      with specialized input variants for size + caching.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/ArroyoSystems/arroyo/blob/main/crates/arroyo/
# src/main.rs clap derive Cli + Subcommand definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'run:run a query as a local pipeline cluster'
    'api:start an Arroyo API server'
    'controller:start an Arroyo controller'
    'cluster:start a complete Arroyo cluster'
    'worker:start an Arroyo worker'
    'compiler:start an Arroyo compiler server'
    'node:start an Arroyo node server'
    'migrate:run database migrations on configured Postgres database'
    'visualize:visualize a query plan'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-c --config)'{-c+,--config=}'[path to Arroyo config file (TOML or YAML)]:file:_files -g "*.(toml|yaml|yml)"' \
    '--config-dir=[directory to look for configuration files]:directory:_directories' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'arroyo subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            run)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-n --name)'{-n+,--name=}'[name for this pipeline]:name:' \
                    '(-s --state-dir)'{-s+,--state-dir=}'[directory or URL where checkpoints and metadata will be written and restored from]:dir:_directories' \
                    '(-p --parallelism)'{-p+,--parallelism=}'[number of parallel subtasks (default 1)]:count:' \
                    '(-f --force)'{-f,--force}'[force pipeline start even if state file does not match query]' \
                    '1:query (file path / URL / `-` for stdin):_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            visualize)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-o --open)'{-o,--open}'[open the visualization in the browser]' \
                    '1:query (file path / URL / `-` for stdin):_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            migrate)
                _arguments -s \
                    '--wait=[seconds to wait for Postgres readiness before running migrations]:seconds:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
